5|$|Bach {{structured}} the cantata in two parts, four {{movements to}} be performed before <b>the</b> <b>sermon,</b> three after <b>the</b> <b>sermon.</b> Both parts begin with a sinfonia. Bach scored it for an alto soloist and a Baroque instrumental ensemble of two oboes (Ob), taille (Ot), obbligato solo organ (Org), two violins (Vl), viola (Va), and basso continuo (Bc).|$|E
5|$|It is unsure when <b>the</b> <b>sermon</b> was {{actually}} given, but some critics suggest it was read {{immediately following the}} publication of Swift's Letter to the Whole People of Ireland while others place it in October 1724.|$|E
5|$|Swift {{relies on}} Gospel of Matthew in this sermon (Swift quotes from <b>the</b> <b>Sermon</b> on the Mount, Matthew 7:12) {{instead of the}} other Gospels; this is {{standard}} practice for Swift, because the Gospel features a simple, non-controversial history that complements Swift's religious views.|$|E
